============================================================
p=11, m=5

  Degree-4 Walsh of alpha_2 (3-3 pairs) and c_5:
             quad  q_ab  q_cd        h4_a2        h4_c5     h2_c3_ab*cd     ratio_a2
  (0,1,2,3) q=(5,5):       8.2500     -16.5000          0.0000       0.0000
  (0,1,2,4) q=(5,5):       8.2500     -16.5000          0.0000       0.0000
  (0,1,3,4) q=(5,3):       8.2500     -16.5000          0.0000       0.0000
  (0,2,3,4) q=(3,3):      -8.2500      16.5000          0.0000       0.0000
  (1,2,3,4) q=(3,3):       8.2500     -16.5000          0.0000       0.0000

  ANALYSIS: Alpha_2 degree-4 Walsh vs c_3 degree-2 products
  Since c_3 is CONSTANT (=55), its degree-2 Walsh is 0!
  So the product h2[c3]*h2[c3] = 0 for ALL pairings.
  The nonzero alpha_2 Walsh must come from the STRUCTURE of
  disjoint cycles, not just the total count.

  Alpha_2 values: [495, 506, 517, 550]
  c_5 values: [484, 550, 572, 594]

  c_5 -> alpha_2 mapping:
    c_5=484: alpha_2 = [550]
    c_5=550: alpha_2 = [517]
    c_5=572: alpha_2 = [506]
    c_5=594: alpha_2 = [495]

DONE.
